title: Bluebird ES6 compatibility
body:
_This PR is a work-in-progress._  
Fixes #4112.  Duplicate of PR #4788, but the latter hasn't been touched in a while.

To properly support ES6, this type definition needs to be split into a couple declarations to support the different scenarios in which it might be used.
#### To-Do
- [ ] Split `BluebirdPromise` class into two interfaces: `BluebirdPromise` and `BluebirdPromiseConstructor`
  - This allows us to extend the built-in `Promise` and `PromiseConstructor` interfaces from `lib.es6.d.ts`
- [ ] `declare module "bluebird" {}`
  - allows us to `require('bluebird')`
- [ ] `declare module Promise {}`
  - exposes all Bluebird interfaces on the global `Promise` variable
#### Questions
- [ ] Do we need to write a declaration that will `declare var Promise: BluebirdPromiseConstructor;`?
  - In other words, will our declaration ever be used without `lib.es6.d.ts`?  
    Or does `tsc` _always_ load `lib.es6.d.ts`?
#### Automatically generating multiple versions of the declaration

Ideally, we'd have several bluebird declarations:
- "bluebird.d.ts": declares external "bluebird" module
- "bluebird-global.d.ts": extends global `Promise` variable _and_ declares external "bluebird" module

Due to TS quirks, the latter can't merely reference the former.

JS templating systems are a dime-a-dozen.  Devise a simple solution for building multiple versions of the declarations with a build script.  Something like C++ `#ifdef` proprocessor.  Make sure the source code is still valid .d.ts so that IDE Intellisense still works while writing declarations.

title: Allow 'chance' to be callable, and also self-referential as a module
body:
Previously, when using ES6-style syntax as so:

``` TypeScript
import { Chance } from "chance";
```

one could only _call_ `Chance`:

``` TypeScript
var chance = Chance();
```

This change allows users to also construct `Chance` as the actual runtime permits:

```
var chance = new Chance():
```

It also accounts for the fact that Chance behaves the same whether constructed or called.
